Intuition
my approach would be , i will be using recursion and backtracking .

the idea is that evvery recursive call , i am standing at a particular starting index , i try every possible substring that begins here,

if the chosen substring is palindrome i include it in my current diary, and recursivel solve remaining parts of string , After the recursive call finishes, I remove that substring so I can try the next possible choice.

my choices are ,
not to take or skip a characteer,
My choice is deciding where my current substring should end.

So for every ending index from start to n-1, I form one substring:

part = s[start:end+1]

If this substring is a palindrome, I choose it and continue recursively.

State

The recursive function is:

backtrack(start)

Here, start represents the first index that has not been partitioned yet.

Base Case

If start == n, it means I have partitioned the entire string into valid palindrome substrings.

So I store a copy of my current partition in the result.

Backtracking

After exploring one choice, I remove the last substring from diary so that I can try the next possible substring.

Complexity
Time complexity:
≈ O(2^n*n)

Space complexity:
Auxilary space - O(n)

Code
class Solution:
    def partition(self, s: str) -> List[List[str]]:
        def palindrome_check(word):
            left = 0
            right = len(word) - 1
            while left <= right:
                if word[left] != word[right]:
                    return False
                left += 1
                right -=1
            return True
            
        result , diary , n = [] , [] , len(s)
        def get_all_parts(start):
            if start == n:
                result.append(diary.copy())
                return
                
            for end in range(start ,n):
                part = s[start:end+1]   
                if palindrome_check(part) == True:
                    diary.append(part)
                    get_all_parts(end+1)
                    diary.pop()
            return
        get_all_parts(0)
        return result      
